<h4 class="margin-top">Intel has one of the most successful investment portfolios in the industry. What’s the secret sauce?</h4>

<p>
	“We focus on product market fit and teams that can execute. Becoming a successful venture firm takes time, as it takes time to understand the investment landscape and have experience. Intel Capital has been investing for more than 25 years, so we have that knowledge.”
</p>

<p>
	“The lessons, successes, and challenges we’ve seen over the years has come in handy for our current investments. We also have a rigorous internal review process and do deep diligence on our investments before we put money in. This ranges from product technology, financials, sales pipelines, customer interviews, and doing our own checks beyond what the companies tell us.”
</p>

<h4 class="margin-top">
	What is one of the biggest lessons you’ve learned in your experience as a venture capitalist?
</h4>

<p>
	“Markets move. You can have a good company trying to find the right market, but as technology, the economy, and other factors change, many startups end up out of business. A great example of markets moving is the mobile shift we are currently experiencing. This is one of the biggest shifts in the industry. Companies that are not embracing mobile will have a pretty hard time succeeding in the future. As a venture capitalist, I’ve learned that it’s important to not only look at the initial target market, but how that market are moving.”
</p>

<h4 class="margin-top">
	What “cutting edge” technologies are you most passionate about at the moment?
</h4>
<p>
	“I’m quite passionate about machine learning. Machine learning is a universal term, but it’s interesting applied to devices that we use on a daily basis, professional or personal. With the advent of speech recognition and image recognition, our daily use devices are getting smarter but we are not there yet. There is plenty of opportunity to get smarter through machine learning technologies and I see a wave coming soon.”
</p>

<p>
	“Identity and authentication based technologies (not just biometrics) are fascinating as well, such as startups working on technology and devices that can understand and recognize me before I even type up my password.”
</p>

<h4 class="margin-top">
	What’s the next biggest thing startups and VCs should be on the lookout for?
</h4>
<p>
	“Connected devices. You can call it internet of things or connectivity everywhere. I envision that we are not going to be carrying devices anymore. There will be screens everywhere, and those screens will show me where I’m going, and who I am.”
</p>

<p>
	“I should not need a device. I should be able to go into a meeting and log into a device that’s already there. Same when I enter the car or when I’m at work. Carrying a device will become an archaic thing but it will take a few years to happen.”
</p>

<h4 class="margin-top">
	What are your thoughts on people the startup industry bubble?
</h4>
<p>
	“Valuations have risen to be on the higher side and there is potential for correction, but good startups with good market traction will not see a correction. Valuations need to be tied to company revenue not just hype. Companies that have raised money on hype vs revenue will see a correction, especially when public markets collapse.
</p>

