<h4 class="margin-top">
	Are “unicorns” affecting valuations and the startup ecosystem?
</h4>

<p>
	“Unicorns are a fairly well used term. You can call them leaders, stars, unicorns, but that doesn’t change the concept. The fact that a company can go from paper concept to IPO level in 6 years is phenomenal. I salute those entrepreneurs that can do that. They deserve to be unicorns, and yes, they are affecting the startup ecosystem and valuations.”
</p>

<p>
	“The venture capital industry can sometimes be a rat race. VCs will see companies like Uber be successful, and then try to find the next one. Most of the time, this is a wild goose chase. If you talk to successful CEOs, they’ll likely tell you that part of their success is timing and luck. The fact that they got to huge scale or exit is all because of timing and luck. Trying to chase the next big thing is like trying to predict the future.”
</p>

